    <h1 id="great-blue-heron-faq-and-fun-facts">Great Blue Heron FAQ and Fun Facts</h1>
<h2 id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<p><strong>Are Great Blue Herons endangered?</strong>
No. The species is IUCN Least Concern with an increasing population (~700,000 breeders), though the Pacific <em>fannini</em> subspecies is of Special Concern in Canada, Florida's "great white heron" is Endangered on BirdLife's list, and Maine reports steep local declines.<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Do Great Blue Herons mate for life?</strong>
No — they are seasonally monogamous, choosing a new mate most years, though pairs that reunite at a colony may re-bond quickly.<sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup><sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>How big are they, really?</strong>
Up to 4.5 ft tall, 97–137 cm long, 167–201 cm wingspan — yet only about 5–6 lb, thanks to hollow bones.<sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup><sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Is it a crane?</strong>
No. Cranes fly with necks outstretched, eat mostly plants, and can't perch in trees; herons fly with necks folded, eat animals, and nest in trees.<sup id="fnref:7"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:7">7</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Can they hunt at night?</strong>
Yes — rod-rich eyes give them excellent night vision; they are among the only members of their genus that forage after dark.<sup id="fnref:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>What do they eat besides fish?</strong>
Frogs, snakes (up to ~3.5 ft water snakes), turtles, crayfish, crabs, insects, voles, gophers, mice, muskrats, even rabbits and other birds.<sup id="fnref:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>How long do they live?</strong>
About 15 years on average; the banding record is 23–25 years. But ~2 of 3 die in their first year.<sup id="fnref:10"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:10">10</a></sup><sup id="fnref:11"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:11">11</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Why did one squawk at me?</strong>
You surprised it. The harsh "frawnk" is an alarm call that can run 20 seconds.<sup id="fnref:12"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:12">12</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Are they dangerous to people?</strong>
No — but never handle one: the lightning-fast bill strike can cause serious injury, and handlers have been struck at the eyes. Call a wildlife rehabilitator for injured birds.<sup id="fnref2:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Do they migrate?</strong>
Some do, some don't. Northern and eastern birds head south as water freezes (some to Central America); Pacific coast, Florida, and Galápagos birds stay year-round.<sup id="fnref:13"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:13">13</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Where do they sleep?</strong>
Communally, usually 5–20 birds in tall trees near water.<sup id="fnref:14"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:14">14</a></sup></p>
<p><strong>Is the white one in Florida a different bird?</strong>
It's the "great white heron" — officially a subspecies of the Great Blue, but with genetic and behavioral evidence for full species status; look for pale legs to rule out Great Egret.<sup id="fnref:15"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:15">15</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="twenty-fun-facts">Twenty fun facts</h2>
<ol>
<li>The scientific name means "heron heron" — Latin <em>ardea</em> + Greek <em>erōdios</em>.<sup id="fnref:16"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:16">16</a></sup></li>
<li>One GPS-tracked heron, "Harper," flew <strong>1,424 miles nonstop over the ocean in 38.6 hours</strong>.<sup id="fnref:17"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:17">17</a></sup></li>
<li>Herons groom with <strong>powder down</strong> — self-generating feather dust that soaks up fish slime.<sup id="fnref2:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></li>
<li>The comb on their middle toe is called a <strong>pectinate claw</strong>.<sup id="fnref:18"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:18">18</a></sup></li>
<li>In Nova Scotia, <strong>98% of one population's diet was flounder</strong>.<sup id="fnref2:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup></li>
<li>In Idaho, <strong>24–40% of the diet was voles</strong> — these "water birds" are serious mousers.<sup id="fnref3:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup></li>
<li>They can swallow fish up to <strong>60 cm (2 ft) long</strong> — and occasionally choke trying.<sup id="fnref4:9"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:9">9</a></sup><sup id="fnref3:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></li>
<li>Chicks gain <strong>40× their hatch weight in 8 weeks</strong>.<sup id="fnref2:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></li>
<li>Eggs are <strong>pale blue</strong> and fade as incubation progresses.<sup id="fnref2:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></li>
<li>Nests grow from 20-inch platforms to <strong>4-foot-wide, 3.5-foot-deep</strong> fortresses over years.<sup id="fnref3:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></li>
<li>Colonies can exceed <strong>500 nests</strong>, yet the same birds hunt alone all winter.<sup id="fnref4:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></li>
<li>A family of four burns about <strong>2,000 calories a day</strong>.<sup id="fnref3:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></li>
<li>Seattle made the Great Blue Heron its <strong>official city bird in 2003</strong>.<sup id="fnref:19"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:19">19</a></sup></li>
<li>Vancouver's Stanley Park colony has been nesting there <strong>since 1921</strong>.<sup id="fnref4:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></li>
<li>Herons sometimes nest on <strong>channel markers, duck blinds, and beaver mounds</strong>.<sup id="fnref5:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup></li>
<li>Parents incubate through <strong>snowstorms</strong> and have fended off Great Horned Owls on camera.<sup id="fnref:20"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:20">20</a></sup></li>
<li>The first-hatched chick may bully younger siblings to death — <strong>siblicide</strong> is normal.<sup id="fnref:21"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:21">21</a></sup></li>
<li>At hatcheries, herons were found to eat <strong>mostly diseased fish</strong> — unintentional quality control.<sup id="fnref3:8"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:8">8</a></sup></li>
<li>They occasionally turn up in <strong>Europe</strong> — one made the British List in 2008.<sup id="fnref:22"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:22">22</a></sup></li>
<li>The genus <em>Ardea</em> is at least <strong>15 million years old</strong>.<sup id="fnref:23"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:23">23</a></sup></li>
</ol>
